{"title_page": "Iv\u00e1n Marulanda", "text_new": "{{spanish name|Marulanda|Gomez}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name= Iv\u00e1n Marulanda\n| image=    File:IVAN MARULANDA6.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| order=\n| office = Ambassador of Colombia to the [[Food and Agriculture Organization|United Nations Agencies for Food and Agriculture]]\n| term_start= 1991\n| term_end = 1992\n| president= [[Cesar Gaviria]]\n| predecessor=\n| successor= \n| office2 = Member of [[Constituent Assembly of Colombia]]\n| term_start2= 5 February 1991\n| term_end2 = 1 June 1991\n| president2 =[[Cesar Gaviria]]\n\n| successor2 =\n| office3 = [[Senate of Colombia|Senator of the Republic of Colombia]]\n| term_start3 = 1986\n| term_end3 = 1990\n| president3 = [[Virgilio Barco Vargas]]\n\n| successor3= \n| office4        = City Councillor of [[Medellin]]\n| term_start4     = 1 January 1984\n| term_end4       = 1 January 1985\n| office5 = Mayor of [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]]\n| term_start5   = 1 January 1974\n| term_end5    = 1 January 1975\n| birth_date={{Birth date and age|1946|06|04|df=yes}}\n| birth_place=[[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]], [[Risaralda Department|Risaralda]]\n| party= [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|Liberal Party]]<br />Compromiso Ciuadadano (current)\n|otherparty   = [[Green Alliance (Colombia)|Green Alliance]]\n| spouse= \n|children = Two\n| alma_mater = [[University of Antioquia]]\n| profession = [[Economist]], [[Politician]]\n}}\n\n'''Luis Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez''' (born June 4, 1946) is [[Colombia]]n politician and economist. A member of the [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|Colombian Liberal Party]], he was elected Senator in 1986 and served one term. He was the nominee of his party for [[Vice President of Colombia]] in the [[2006 Colombian presidential election|2006 Presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivanmarulanda.com/about/ |title=Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez &#124; Iv\u00e1n Marulanda |website=Ivanmarulanda.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nMarulanda was born in [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]], [[Risaralda Department|Risaralda]], and graduated with an economics degree from the [[University of Antioquia]]. He served as the Mayor of [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]] in 1974 and then went onto become the general secretary at the [[Ministry of Economic Development (Colombia)|Ministry of Economic Development]]. During this period he became involved directly with [[Luis Carlos Galan]] and his [[New Liberalism (Colombia)|New Liberalism movement]]. As part of [[New Liberalism (Colombia)|New Liberalism]], he was the campaign director of the movement in Antioquia was elected city councillor of [[Medellin]], the second largest city in Colombia and the capital of [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]]. In his role as campaign director for Antioquia, he was the person who warned Galan that [[Pablo Escobar]] wanted to infiltrate the movement in order to become a politician, this led to Luis Carlos Galan denouncing Escobar on the stage and denying Escobar membership of the movement.<ref name=\"eltiempo1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento-2013/CMS-5525028 |title=Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez no claudica - Archivo Digital de Noticias de Colombia y el Mundo desde 1.990 |website=Eltiempo.com |date=2009-06-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> In 1986, he was elected Senator alongside [[Luis Carlos Galan]]. In 1987, the New Liberalism movement decided to rejoin the [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|Liberal Party]]. He was elected a member of the Constituent assembly in 1991, charged with drafting the [[Colombian Constitution of 1991]] after president [[Cesar Gaviria]] and Congress decided to dissolve the [[Colombian Constitution of 1886|Constitution of 1886]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wradio.com.co/noticias/actualidad/el-ex-constituyente-ivan-marulanda-gomez-es-la-formula-vicepresidencial-de-horacio-serpa/20060328/nota/264557.aspx |title=El ex constituyente Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez es la f\u00f3rmula vicepresidencial de Horacio Serpa &#124; Actualidad &#124; W Radio Colombia |website=Wradio.com.co |date=2006-03-28 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAfter the new constitution was drafted and the constituent assembly dissolved, Ivan Marulanda was appointed by [[Cesar Gaviria]] as an Ambassador to the United Nations in 1991. He also held the diplomatic post of Ambassador to the [[Food and Agriculture Organization|United Nations Agencies for Food and Agriculture]] between 1992-1994.<ref name=\"eltiempo1\"/>\n\nIn 2002, he became part of the [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|National Council of the Liberal Party]] and in 2006 he was chosen as the Liberal nominee for Vice President, running alongside [[Horacio Serpa]]. They finished third, behind incumbent president [[Alvaro Uribe]] and the newly formed left wing party [[Alternative Democratic Pole]]. He was a candidate for president in the 2010 election but lost out on Liberal Party nomination to former Defence Minister and Senator [[Rafael Pardo]].\n\nMarulanda recently served as an adviser to [[Sergio Fajardo]] during his tenure as governor of [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]] from 2012-2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marulanda, Ivan}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Colombian politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name|Marulanda|Gomez}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name= Iv\u00e1n Marulanda\n| image=    File:IVAN MARULANDA6.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| order=\n| office = Ambassador of Colombia to the [[Food and Agriculture Organization|United Nations Agencies for Food and Agriculture]]\n| term_start= 1991\n| term_end = 1992\n| president= [[Cesar Gaviria]]\n| predecessor=\n| successor= \n| office2 = Member of [[Constituent Assembly of Colombia]]\n| term_start2= 5 February 1991\n| term_end2 = 1 June 1991\n| president2 =[[Cesar Gaviria]]\n\n| successor2 =\n| office3 = [[Senate of Colombia|Senator of the Republic of Colombia]]\n| term_start3 = 1986\n| term_end3 = 1990\n| president3 = [[Virgilio Barco Vargas]]\n\n| successor3= \n| office4        = City Councillor of [[Medellin]]\n| term_start4     = 1 January 1984\n| term_end4       = 1 January 1985\n| office5 = Mayor of [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]]\n| term_start5   = 1 January 1974\n| term_end5    = 1 January 1975\n| birth_date={{Birth date and age|1946|06|04|df=yes}}\n| birth_place=[[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]], [[Risaralda Department|Risaralda]]\n| party= [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|Liberal Party]]<br />Compromiso Ciuadadano (current)\n|otherparty   = [[Green Alliance (Colombia)|Green Alliance]]\n| spouse= \n|children = Two\n| alma_mater = [[University of Antioquia]]\n| profession = [[Economist]], [[Politician]]\n}}\n\n'''Luis Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez''' (born June 4, 1946) is [[Colombia]]n politician and economist. A member of the [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|Colombian Liberal Party]], he was elected Senator in 1986 and served one term. He was the nominee of his party for [[Vice President of Colombia]] in the [[2006 Colombian presidential election|2006 Presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivanmarulanda.com/about/ |title=Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez &#124; Iv\u00e1n Marulanda |website=Ivanmarulanda.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nMarulanda was Born in [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]], [[Risaralda Department|Risaralda]], and graduated with an economics degree from the [[University of Antioquia]]. He served as the Mayor of [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]] in 1974 and then went onto become the general secretary at the [[Ministry of Economic Development (Colombia)|Ministry of Economic Development]]. During this period he became involved directly with [[Luis Carlos Galan]] and his [[New Liberalism (Colombia)|New Liberalism movement]]. As part of [[New Liberalism (Colombia)|New Liberalism]], he was the campaign director of the movement in Antioquia was elected city councillor of [[Medellin]], the second largest city in Colombia and the capital of [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]]. In his role as campaign director for Antioquia, he was the person who warned Galan that [[Pablo Escobar]] wanted to infiltrate the movement in order to become a politician, this led to Luis Carlos Galan denouncing Escobar on the stage and denying Escobar membership of the movement.<ref name=\"eltiempo1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento-2013/CMS-5525028 |title=Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez no claudica - Archivo Digital de Noticias de Colombia y el Mundo desde 1.990 |website=Eltiempo.com |date=2009-06-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> In 1986, he was elected Senator alongside [[Luis Carlos Galan]]. In 1987, the New Liberalism movement decided to rejoin the [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|Liberal Party]]. He was elected a member of the Constituent assembly in 1991, charged with drafting the [[Colombian Constitution of 1991]] after president [[Cesar Gaviria]] and Congress decided to dissolve the [[Colombian Constitution of 1886|Constitution of 1886]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wradio.com.co/noticias/actualidad/el-ex-constituyente-ivan-marulanda-gomez-es-la-formula-vicepresidencial-de-horacio-serpa/20060328/nota/264557.aspx |title=El ex constituyente Iv\u00e1n Marulanda G\u00f3mez es la f\u00f3rmula vicepresidencial de Horacio Serpa &#124; Actualidad &#124; W Radio Colombia |website=Wradio.com.co |date=2006-03-28 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAfter the new constitution was drafted and the constituent assembly dissolved, Ivan Marulanda was appointed by [[Cesar Gaviria]] as an Ambassador to the United Nations in 1991. He also held the diplomatic post of Ambassador to the [[Food and Agriculture Organization|United Nations Agencies for Food and Agriculture]] between 1992-1994.<ref name=\"eltiempo1\"/>\n\nIn 2002, he became part of the [[Liberal Party (Colombia)|National Council of the Liberal Party]] and in 2006 he was chosen as the Liberal nominee for Vice President, running alongside [[Horacio Serpa]]. They finished third, behind incumbent president [[Alvaro Uribe]] and the newly formed left wing party [[Alternative Democratic Pole]]. He was a candidate for president in the 2010 election but lost out on Liberal Party nomination to former Defence Minister and Senator [[Rafael Pardo]].\n\nMarulanda recently served as an adviser to [[Sergio Fajardo]] during his tenure as governor of [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]] from 2012-2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marulanda, Ivan}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Colombian politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: was Born \u2192 was born", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iv%C3%A1n_Marulanda"}
